When Jules Evola speaks on mountaineering, it's important that he considers the objective reality of the mountainous environment instead of just physical risk, exertion, grit, etc. He mentions that even riding in an airplane partakes in some of its effects.

Thus taking the cabin lift to a peak with zero effort is probably closer to the "spiritual" mountaineering than climbing walls in an indoor gym at zero altitude. Also he hated the idea of sportive training/recreation being associated with work, "workout" as a concept is tiresome.

Have not read the entire "A Handbook for Youth" by Evola yet (shame on me), but he speaks on Mensur and academic fencing there and (if we follow the above logic) not actually having your face slashed open in fencing probably makes much of the activity meaningless in the same way.
